body:
While debugging #2508, I found that a dangling reference.

I am willing to make a PR to fix this issue.
Any feedback is appreciated. ( I am not familiar with verilated C++ code especially about naming convention and thread safe for `--threads` ).

### Example to show the symptom
```systemverilog
module t;
   function automatic void set_abc(output string s);
      s = "abc";
   endfunction
   export "DPI-C" function set_abc;
endmodule
```

### Generated C++ code
```c++
void Vt::set_abc(const char** s) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt::set_abc\n"); );
    // Variables
    std::string s__Vcvt;
    // Body
    static int __Vfuncnum = -1;
    if (VL_UNLIKELY(__Vfuncnum==-1)) { __Vfuncnum = Verilated::exportFuncNum("set_abc"); }
    const VerilatedScope* __Vscopep = Verilated::dpiScope();
    Vt__Vcb_set_abc_t __Vcb = (Vt__Vcb_set_abc_t)(VerilatedScope::exportFind(__Vscopep, __Vfuncnum));
    (*__Vcb)((Vt__Syms*)(__Vscopep->symsp()), s__Vcvt);
    *s = s__Vcvt.c_str();  // <=== s__Vcvt is a local variable, so *s will be a dangling pointer!
}
```
`s__Vcvt` is a local variable, so s__Vcvt.c_str() will be invalid after exiting the function.

IEEE 1800-2017 H.8.10 requires SystemVerilog side to manage the lifetime of strings.

### Fix that I am thinking
Add a member variable `__dpiExportCvt` to the top module of VL_MODULE.
```c++
    // INTERNAL VARIABLES
    // Internals; generally not touched by application code
    Vt_dpi_export_string__Syms* __VlSymsp;  // Symbol table
    std::vector<std::unique_ptr<std::string[]>> __dpiExportCvt;  // Add this member variable
```
Note that `std::unique_ptr<std::string[]> ` is used instead of `std::unique_ptr<std::string>` because I will add unpacked array support later.


Then use the `__dpiExportCvt` in each export wrapper as below.
``` c++
    auto& __dpiExportCvt = ((Vt_dpi_export_string__Syms*) __Vscopep->symsp())->TOPp->__dpiExportCvt;
    __dpiExportCvt.clear();  // delete temporary objects created in the previous call
    __dpiExportCvt.emplace_back(new std::string[1]);  // Create the temporary object
    std::string& s__Vcvt = __dpiExportCvt.back()[0];
    // do something to s__Vcvt;
   *s = s__Vcvt.c_str();  // Now  *s is valid until the next call of any exported function
```

The returned pointer will be valid until the next call of any exported functions with `output string` because 
`__dpiExportCvt` is shared among them. I think this behavior is compliant to IEEE standard as it says:

>  If it is desired to refer to the string’s valueat some point in the future, the user shall copy the string value to memory owned by the C domain.
